Man City 2012

>Currently the record books for the VFL/AFL start in 1897, Carter however says the official year should be 1870 which changes a major sticking point for fans.
>Carter was a former commissioner and Geelong President who is aiming to include the Victorian Football Association years before eight clubs broke away and formed the VFL.
>The book would make a drastic change to one of the biggest sticking points in arguments among footy fans, who has won the most premierships.

>AFL boss Gillon McLachlan said the book launch was a heavy night, but said the topic would for sure open up the debate.

That sounds pretty reasonable. I think recent achievements tell a lot more about how a boxer fares than how they fought 10 years ago. After all we’re trying to determine who is the best active boxer, not who would hypothetically be the best in some kind of vague “prime”. I really think boxing is a sport of youre only as good as your last few fights. Not meant to be taken hyper literally and past achievements should be taken into account, but I find oftentimes people get hung up on the past to the point where they may gloss over whats weak or strong about a fighter’s most recent performance. Injuries, changes in tactics, stamina problems, so on and so forth. I like a more by the numbers type deal. Judging on technique alone only says so much, but at the same time I find we dont need to over scrutinize someone’s resume to the point of exhaustion. If you dont know the details surrounding the fight the outcome is on paper is not that helpful by itself. You need to explain how they won and what makes them better than everyone else.

The other problem with p4p lists is they dont really factor in styles. Some fighter might technically be ranked worse than another, maybe by a large margin, but because its a particularly bad matchup for the styles this sort of boosts one of the fighters. Boxing isnt so simple to give people numerical numbers.

I also dont think losses should count THAT badly against someone’s scores. Getting hung up on undefeated records is a meme. The greats of old rarely had undefeated records and the few who did it was because of an early retirement. When the best fight the best, someone loses. Thats why its important to understand the details of a fight. Simply saying this guy lost and this guy won doesnt mean a whole lot by itself.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>128835051
Im glad you asked. It starts with having actually won a fight as the smaller guy
So that means no Luke Fury or anybody else (haney, josh taylor) who has only won fights against fighters with smaller frames than them
Then I look at the original 8 weight classes (fly, bantam, feather, light, welter, middle, light heavy, heavy) and see who the champions are and how they got there. 2 of these weight classes have Undisputed champions, but only one of those champions won a fight as the smaller guy so Inoue is pound for pound #1

Then I look at people that are nearly undisputed/3 belt champions. There are 3 of those in the original weight classes, Artur Beterbiev, Errol Spence, and Oleksandr Usyk. Both Beterbiev and Usyk win fights as the smaller guy, but a slight edge to Usyk puts him at #2 because of my next criteria

Achievements in the other (super/junior) weight classes
Usyk was undisputed at a lower weight class, whereas Beterbiev and Spence have spent their careers at the 1 weight class. This is also where fighters whose current achievements are in super/junior classes can be ranked, like Canelo and Jermell Charlo

Next we look for partial/unified champions in the other classes who win as the smaller fighter, so that's where you place Stephen Fulton and Kenshiro Teraji

And finally the "other factors" section, where you place original 8 fighters on hot streaks aka the eye test fighters, like Crawford and Bivol

1. Inoue
2. Usyk
3. Beterbiev
4. Spence
5. Canelo
6. Jermell Charlo
7. Fulton
8. Teraji
9. Crawford
10. Bivol

It's a complex science, and maybe even a bullshit one, but at the end of the day, 'pound-for-pound' is a concept that has been around since the SRR days, so it's a piece of boxing history whether you like it or not
For me personally...
1. The best way to gauge P4P greatness is a fighter winning big fights and/or belts in multiple divisions, as this shows they can close the size gap using sheer skill (i.e. Usyk vs AJ, SRR at middleweight, Duran, Pac etc.), however this has been corrupted by fighters cutting waterweight the day before fights, junior/super divisions and the abundance of belts hasn't helped. I like Canelo, but Canelo is only really a 2-weight world champ and a 1-weight world champ going by vintage standards
2. So the second way is how well a fighter has cleaned out their division. This also factors in things like title defences and WHO you've beaten. Ali only fought in one division, but defended his belts dozens of times and beat many other HOF fighters. The implication is that if you destroy your division, you're clearly an amazing boxer who COULD compete at higher weight classes. Point 1 vs point 2 is basically Bud vs Spence
3. The final and most subjective way of judging P4P greatness, and this applies quite often to modern fighters who like to stick to one division for a long time and can't get big fights, is the eye-test. It's pretty self-explanatory. It's normally used to support either point 1 or 2

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>128836557
Fasted training will burn both fat and muscle. It will burn fat because your body will need a fuel source and it will also ''burn'' muscle because your skeletal muscles are viewed by the body as protein reservoirs. If you want to burn fat slowly and keep your muscles then just do normal workouts with energy foods beforehand. When I go to the gym for 2 hours all of the oats and shit I eat in the morning gets used up. If you want to really deepdive this topic, you need to eat protein even when you're not working out because your body will use skeletal muscle for more important things like your brain, heart, organs, digestive tract, skin etc. I stopped training in October because my job is busy as fuck in November and December, and even though I didn't put on any fat, I lost the definition in my quads, because I had a shitty eating schedule. Also a word of advice don't get hooked on cringey shit like bodybuilding or powerlifting (extreme levels of cringe). ALWAYS box every single gym session, even if it's just a warmup or something

>>128838071
>Look at the champs of 168 before Canelo came along. Say that Plant or BJS had held all the belts at that weight, would we really recognize them as p4p on that alone?

This is a fun hypothetical but the underlying issue is simple. They never would be unified champs. It's almost impossible to be a 'fake' unified champion because there are too many real fighters at every weight class. The sport of boxing asks too much of top level fighters to collect all the belts on accident and actually continue to defend them. If you are a unified champion and have been for a year plus, it's because you are a real fighter.

All that being said I get your underlying concern. Not all weight classes are created equal talent-wise, some have depth and others don't. My personal pound for pound system is designed to remove all emotion/eye-test from p4p lists because opinions on the quality of fighters can shift very rapidly and there is rarely consensus. By focusing on just a few criteria that are close to universally agreed upon in the community (1. The big weight classes 2. Undisputed/unified champions 3. Winning fights as the smaller man) I think you hone in on a pretty hard to argue with list without resorting to purely emotional complaints

And I think it keeps to the literal spirit of pound for pound as in "this boxer, despite not being the most intimidating size-wise, defies the odds to be a dominant champion with the use of their boxing skills"

Pot the 9 ball to win the rack
Object ball is the lowest numbered ball on the table
Have to either pot or hit a rail after contact with object ball
Fouls give opponent ball in hand
Plants are allowed, e.g. hitting the 1 but potting the 9 wins the rack
Only weird rule is the push out after the break, you can nominate to "push out" after the break (either player, so long as it's the first shot after the break), which allows you to hit the cue ball but without having to hit the object ball or a rail. Your opponent can then decide whether to play or put you back in after the push out.

>>128849126
And i want to clear out a thing my friend just explained to me. The program has that 95% for "team to prevail in achieving their objective". Meaning for Arouca - Benfica. Benfica has the initial objective as "winning this game" , so away win 1.30, which the model has at 95%. At 0-0 benfica has primary objective "to score the winning goal" the whole game. Or if they take the lead and it's 0-1 the objective is "to hold on to the win" until the end". But if arouca takes the lead in min 10 and it's 1-0, Benfica will have changed it's primary objective to "to equalize" and it's secondary objective "to win". And it tails the first objective for 95% chance of achieving for the duration of the whole 90 minutes, and the secondary objective (benfica to win) percentages are changing in real time depending of how much time left there is. Meaning if arouca scores for 1-0 in the 10' min benfica to win will not have 95% chance, but around maybe 80% (cause they'll have time to turn it around) but if arouca scores for 1-0 in the 80th min the percentage for benfica to turn it around will probably be around 33%. But the percentage for the new primary objective (at 1-0, on benfica to equalize) will remain 95% for the entirety of the game, even if it's 1-0 for arouca in the 80' min, the model will still have benfica to score at 95%. If arouca scores for 2-0 it changes primary objective" to score the 1st goal" (at 95%), secondary to "to score the equalizer" at... 70% depending how much time left, and third "to win"
So that explains the (kinda safe bet) of 37 stake out of 200 for benfica to win 1.30 pregame at 95% chance, because the program plans to reback

i thought you had that guy on a DM(d) role?
and with that guy staying put in front of your defence, it means your left back can go forwards to help with the attack
if your issue is conceding, then its probably wise to have your central midfielders on the same line at least as LCM and RCM
if samson is more mobile, have him as a BWM, and thompson as a DLP/CM(s/d)
and if thompson is more mobile keep him as BBM and just have samson as CM(d) - it doesnt matter if the stars go down, you need one of them to sit, BWM(d) chases the ball and keep the structure
id also remove dribble less OR be more expressive, maybe both, your players still arent massively smart at this level so more instructions will make it harder for them
dont be discouraged, only the teams that are significantly better than the rest of the league can expect to hit the ground running at the start of each season
unless you want your team to keep the ball for minutes at a time, then counter in transition will probably help too

>>128857901
The epl is the weathiest league in the world and has access to the most prestigious competitions on the land. Prestige and money is all players care about so that means top english clubs don’t have to worry about losing their best homegrown players to overseas leagues. Once you have this scenario in place, the people who run the top clubs only have to worry about crunching numbers for very specific ends. They don’t have to worry about choosing between one project or the other when they know they still have access to the top talent they can develop on their own and epl money to fall back on, all they need to do is patch up something that allows them to meet a established self imposed criteria (which is probably way lower than fans expect).
Also top clubs aren’t their own isolated entities anymore, they are part of billionaires’ large group of projects and investments, so there’s even a second layer to that self imposed criteria of crunching numbers and expected failures. If they fuck up, they will replace the people in charge, take the loss and move on; if they fuck EVERYTHING up, they will sell the club and move on. It’s all worked out.

So no, this will not “collapse”, unless the whole premier league collapses; and that won’t happen unless all of England and/or UEFA collapse; and that won’t happen unless the whole economic system collapses or someone blows up Europe.

I was a high school senior and the captain of the football team. I had always been competitive, especially when it came to sports. That's why I was extra pumped up for the game against Lionel Messi and his team.

Messi was known for being a tough competitor, but I was confident in my team's abilities. As the game started, I could feel the adrenaline rushing through my veins. The first half was intense, with both teams evenly matched, but we were able to score a goal just before halftime.

In the second half, Messi and his team tried to come back strong, but my teammates and I were determined to win. We worked together like a well-oiled machine, executing our plays flawlessly. And before we knew it, the final whistle blew and we had won the game 3-0.

But what made the win even sweeter was the fact that I scored all three goals, much to Messi's frustration. He tried his best to stop me, but I was on fire that day and couldn't be stopped. The look on his face after the final goal was priceless.

As I celebrated with my teammates, I couldn't help but think about all the hard work and dedication that had gone into that win. It was a feeling of pure satisfaction and joy. And even though it was just a high school game, it was one of the most memorable moments of my life.
